

XPath:  1-Absolute Xpath    2-Relative XPath

Absolute Xpath:
[/html/body/div[1]/div[1]/div[1]/div/div/div/div[2]/div/div[1]/form/div[1]/div[1]/input]
its PATH might be change while upgrading software. and Absolute start from single foreword slash /

Relative XPath [Custom XPath]

Simple of HTML CODE:
(<input id="userId" class="selectors-input jsSelector" title="Email" spellcheck="false" autocomplete="anyrandomstring" name="email" value="" placeholder="Enter email" type="email" onfocus="if (this.hasAttribute('readonly')) {
     this.removeAttribute('readonly');
     // fix for mobile safari to show virtual keyboard
     this.blur();this.focus();}">)


1-      //tagName[@attributeName='value']
Ex:     //tagName[@id='userid']

2-      //tagName[text()='Inner Text']    Ex: <h3>Useful Links for learning</h3>
Ex:     //h3[contains(text(),'Useful Links for learning')] if there is no attribute so we can use like this.

3-      //tagNme[contains(@attribute,'value')]
Ex:     //input[contains(@title,'Email')]

4-      //tagNme[contains(text(),'inner text')]  //it not much unique prefer to use contains as #3
Ex:     //input[contains(placeholder,'enter email')]


Notes:   Multiple XPath: we can use it with (and, or)
Ex:     //tagName[@id='userid' and @title='email']
Ex:     //tagName[@id='userid' or @title='email']
Ex:     (//tagName[@id='userid' or @title='email'])[1]  or sometime with index but this method also not recommends too.




Note:
find Link element by any name:       //a[starts-with(text(),'Amazon')]